4220	ACT IV
4221	
4222	
4223	
4224	SCENE V	Alexandria. MARK ANTONY's camp.
4225	
4226	
4227	[Trumpets sound. Enter MARK ANTONY and EROS; a
4228	Soldier meeting them]
4229	
4230	Soldier	The gods make this a happy day to Antony!
4231	
4232	MARK ANTONY	Would thou and those thy scars had once prevail'd
4233	To make me fight at land!
4234	
4235	Soldier	Hadst thou done so,
4236	The kings that have revolted, and the soldier
4237	That has this morning left thee, would have still
4238	Follow'd thy heels.
4239	
4240	MARK ANTONY	Who's gone this morning?
4241	
4242	Soldier	Who!
4243	One ever near thee: call for Enobarbus,
4244	He shall not hear thee; or from Caesar's camp
4245	Say 'I am none of thine.'
4246	
4247	MARK ANTONY	What say'st thou?
4248	
4249	Soldier	Sir,
4250	He is with Caesar.
4251	
4252	EROS	                  Sir, his chests and treasure
4253	He has not with him.
4254	
4255	MARK ANTONY	Is he gone?
4256	
4257	Soldier	Most certain.
4258	
4259	MARK ANTONY	Go, Eros, send his treasure after; do it;
4260	Detain no jot, I charge thee: write to him--
4261	I will subscribe--gentle adieus and greetings;
4262	Say that I wish he never find more cause
4263	To change a master. O, my fortunes have
4264	Corrupted honest men! Dispatch.--Enobarbus!
4265	
4266	[Exeunt]
4267	
4268	
