4273	
4274	ACT IV
4275	
4276	
4277	
4278	SCENE VI	Alexandria. OCTAVIUS CAESAR's camp.
4279	
4280	
4281	[Flourish. Enter OCTAVIUS CAESAR, AGRIPPA, with
4282	DOMITIUS ENOBARBUS, and others]
4283	
4284	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Go forth, Agrippa, and begin the fight:
4285	Our will is Antony be took alive;
4286	Make it so known.
4287	
4288	AGRIPPA	Caesar, I shall.
4289	
4290	[Exit]
4291	
4292	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	The time of universal peace is near:
4293	Prove this a prosperous day, the three-nook'd world
4294	Shall bear the olive freely.
4295	
4296	[Enter a Messenger]
4297	
4298	Messenger	Antony
4299	Is come into the field.
4300	
4301	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Go charge Agrippa
4302	Plant those that have revolted in the van,
4303	That Antony may seem to spend his fury
4304	Upon himself.
4305	
4306	[Exeunt all but DOMITIUS ENOBARBUS]
4307	
4308	DOMITIUS ENOBARBUS	Alexas did revolt; and went to Jewry on
4309	Affairs of Antony; there did persuade
4310	Great Herod to incline himself to Caesar,
4311	And leave his master Antony: for this pains
4312	Caesar hath hang'd him. Canidius and the rest
4313	That fell away have entertainment, but
4314	No honourable trust. I have done ill;
4315	Of which I do accuse myself so sorely,
4316	That I will joy no more.
4317	
4318	[Enter a Soldier of CAESAR's]
4319	
4320	Soldier	Enobarbus, Antony
4321	Hath after thee sent all thy treasure, with
4322	His bounty overplus: the messenger
4323	Came on my guard; and at thy tent is now
4324	Unloading of his mules.
4325	
4326	DOMITIUS ENOBARBUS	I give it you.
4327	
4328	Soldier	Mock not, Enobarbus.
4329	I tell you true: best you safed the bringer
4330	Out of the host; I must attend mine office,
4331	Or would have done't myself. Your emperor
4332	Continues still a Jove.
4333	
4334	[Exit]
4335	
4336	DOMITIUS ENOBARBUS	I am alone the villain of the earth,
4337	And feel I am so most. O Antony,
4338	Thou mine of bounty, how wouldst thou have paid
4339	My better service, when my turpitude
4340	Thou dost so crown with gold! This blows my heart:
4341	If swift thought break it not, a swifter mean
4342	Shall outstrike thought: but thought will do't, I feel.
4343	I fight against thee! No: I will go seek
4344	Some ditch wherein to die; the foul'st best fits
4345	My latter part of life.
4346	
4347	[Exit]
4348	
4349	
4350	
4351	
4352	ANTONY AND CLEOPATRA
4353	
4354	
4355	ACT IV
4356	
4357	
4358	
4359	SCENE VII	Field of battle between the camps.
4360	
4361	
4362	[Alarum. Drums and trumpets. Enter AGRIPPA
4363	and others]
4364	
4365	AGRIPPA	Retire, we have engaged ourselves too far:
4366	Caesar himself has work, and our oppression
4367	Exceeds what we expected.
4368	
4369	[Exeunt]
4370	
4371	[Alarums. Enter MARK ANTONY and SCARUS wounded]
4372	
4373	SCARUS	O my brave emperor, this is fought indeed!
4374	Had we done so at first, we had droven them home
4375	With clouts about their heads.
4376	
4377	MARK ANTONY	Thou bleed'st apace.
4378	
4379	SCARUS	I had a wound here that was like a T,
4380	But now 'tis made an H.
4381	
4382	MARK ANTONY	They do retire.
4383	
4384	SCARUS	We'll beat 'em into bench-holes: I have yet
4385	Room for six scotches more.
4386	
4387	[Enter EROS]
4388	
4389	EROS	They are beaten, sir, and our advantage serves
4390	For a fair victory.
4391	
4392	SCARUS	Let us score their backs,
4393	And snatch 'em up, as we take hares, behind:
4394	'Tis sport to maul a runner.
4395	
4396	MARK ANTONY	I will reward thee
4397	Once for thy spritely comfort, and ten-fold
4398	For thy good valour. Come thee on.
4399	
4400	SCARUS	I'll halt after.
4401	
4402	[Exeunt]
4403	
4404	
4405	
4406	
4407	ANTONY AND CLEOPATRA
4408	
4409	
4410	ACT IV
4411	
4412	
4413	
4414	SCENE VIII	Under the walls of Alexandria.
4415	
4416	
4417	[Alarum. Enter MARK ANTONY, in a march; SCARUS,
4418	with others]
4419	
4420	MARK ANTONY	We have beat him to his camp: run one before,
4421	And let the queen know of our gests. To-morrow,
4422	Before the sun shall see 's, we'll spill the blood
4423	That has to-day escaped. I thank you all;
4424	For doughty-handed are you, and have fought
4425	Not as you served the cause, but as 't had been
4426	Each man's like mine; you have shown all Hectors.
4427	Enter the city, clip your wives, your friends,
4428	Tell them your feats; whilst they with joyful tears
4429	Wash the congealment from your wounds, and kiss
4430	The honour'd gashes whole.
4431	
4432	[To SCARUS]
4433	
4434	Give me thy hand
4435	
4436	[Enter CLEOPATRA, attended]
4437	
4438	To this great fairy I'll commend thy acts,
4439	Make her thanks bless thee.
4440	
4441	[To CLEOPATRA]
4442	
4443	O thou day o' the world,
4444	Chain mine arm'd neck; leap thou, attire and all,
4445	Through proof of harness to my heart, and there
4446	Ride on the pants triumphing!
4447	
4448	CLEOPATRA	Lord of lords!
4449	O infinite virtue, comest thou smiling from
4450	The world's great snare uncaught?
4451	
4452	MARK ANTONY	My nightingale,
4453	We have beat them to their beds. What, girl!
4454	though grey
4455	Do something mingle with our younger brown, yet ha' we
4456	A brain that nourishes our nerves, and can
4457	Get goal for goal of youth. Behold this man;
4458	Commend unto his lips thy favouring hand:
4459	Kiss it, my warrior: he hath fought to-day
4460	As if a god, in hate of mankind, had
4461	Destroy'd in such a shape.
4462	
4463	CLEOPATRA	I'll give thee, friend,
4464	An armour all of gold; it was a king's.
4465	
4466	MARK ANTONY	He has deserved it, were it carbuncled
4467	Like holy Phoebus' car. Give me thy hand:
4468	Through Alexandria make a jolly march;
4469	Bear our hack'd targets like the men that owe them:
4470	Had our great palace the capacity
4471	To camp this host, we all would sup together,
4472	And drink carouses to the next day's fate,
4473	Which promises royal peril. Trumpeters,
4474	With brazen din blast you the city's ear;
4475	Make mingle with rattling tabourines;
4476	That heaven and earth may strike their sounds together,
4477	Applauding our approach.
4478	
4479	[Exeunt]
4480	
4481	
4482	
4483	
4484	ANTONY AND CLEOPATRA
4485	
4486	
4487	ACT IV
4488	
4489	
4490	
4491	SCENE IX	OCTAVIUS CAESAR's camp.
4492	
4493	
4494	[Sentinels at their post]
4495	
4496	First Soldier	If we be not relieved within this hour,
4497	We must return to the court of guard: the night
4498	Is shiny; and they say we shall embattle
4499	By the second hour i' the morn.
4500	
4501	Second Soldier	This last day was
4502	A shrewd one to's.
4503	
4504	[Enter DOMITIUS ENOBARBUS]
4505	
4506	DOMITIUS ENOBARBUS	                  O, bear me witness, night,--
4507	
4508	Third Soldier	What man is this?
4509	
4510	Second Soldier	                  Stand close, and list him.
4511	
4512	DOMITIUS ENOBARBUS	Be witness to me, O thou blessed moon,
4513	When men revolted shall upon record
4514	Bear hateful memory, poor Enobarbus did
4515	Before thy face repent!
4516	
4517	First Soldier	Enobarbus!
4518	
4519	Third Soldier	Peace!
4520	Hark further.
4521	
4522	DOMITIUS ENOBARBUS	O sovereign mistress of true melancholy,
4523	The poisonous damp of night disponge upon me,
4524	That life, a very rebel to my will,
4525	May hang no longer on me: throw my heart
4526	Against the flint and hardness of my fault:
4527	Which, being dried with grief, will break to powder,
4528	And finish all foul thoughts. O Antony,
4529	Nobler than my revolt is infamous,
4530	Forgive me in thine own particular;
4531	But let the world rank me in register
4532	A master-leaver and a fugitive:
4533	O Antony! O Antony!
4534	
4535	[Dies]
4536	
4537	Second Soldier	Let's speak To him.
4538	
4539	First Soldier	Let's hear him, for the things he speaks
4540	May concern Caesar.
4541	
4542	Third Soldier	Let's do so. But he sleeps.
4543	
4544	First Soldier	Swoons rather; for so bad a prayer as his
4545	Was never yet for sleep.
4546	
4547	Second Soldier	Go we to him.
4548	
4549	Third Soldier	Awake, sir, awake; speak to us.
4550	
4551	Second Soldier	Hear you, sir?
4552	
4553	First Soldier	The hand of death hath raught him.
4554	
4555	[Drums afar off]
4556	
4557	Hark! the drums
4558	Demurely wake the sleepers. Let us bear him
4559	To the court of guard; he is of note: our hour
4560	Is fully out.
4561	
4562	Third Soldier	Come on, then;
4563	He may recover yet.
4564	
4565	[Exeunt with the body]
4566	
4567	
4568	
4569	
4570	ANTONY AND CLEOPATRA
4571	
