4620	
4621	ANTONY AND CLEOPATRA
4622	
4623	
4624	ACT IV
4625	
4626	
4627	SCENE XII	Another part of the same.
4628	
4629	
4630	[Enter MARK ANTONY and SCARUS]
4631	
4632	MARK ANTONY	Yet they are not join'd: where yond pine
4633	does stand,
4634	I shall discover all: I'll bring thee word
4635	Straight, how 'tis like to go.
4636	
4637	[Exit]
4638	
4639	SCARUS	Swallows have built
4640	In Cleopatra's sails their nests: the augurers
4641	Say they know not, they cannot tell; look grimly,
4642	And dare not speak their knowledge. Antony
4643	Is valiant, and dejected; and, by starts,
4644	His fretted fortunes give him hope, and fear,
4645	Of what he has, and has not.
4646	
4647	[Alarum afar off, as at a sea-fight]
4648	
4649	[Re-enter MARK ANTONY]
4650	
4651	MARK ANTONY	All is lost;
4652	This foul Egyptian hath betrayed me:
4653	My fleet hath yielded to the foe; and yonder
4654	They cast their caps up and carouse together
4655	Like friends long lost. Triple-turn'd whore!
4656	'tis thou
4657	Hast sold me to this novice; and my heart
4658	Makes only wars on thee. Bid them all fly;
4659	For when I am revenged upon my charm,
4660	I have done all. Bid them all fly; begone.
4661	
4662	[Exit SCARUS]
4663	
4664	O sun, thy uprise shall I see no more:
4665	Fortune and Antony part here; even here
4666	Do we shake hands. All come to this? The hearts
4667	That spaniel'd me at heels, to whom I gave
4668	Their wishes, do discandy, melt their sweets
4669	On blossoming Caesar; and this pine is bark'd,
4670	That overtopp'd them all. Betray'd I am:
4671	O this false soul of Egypt! this grave charm,--
4672	Whose eye beck'd forth my wars, and call'd them home;
4673	Whose bosom was my crownet, my chief end,--
4674	Like a right gipsy, hath, at fast and loose,
4675	Beguiled me to the very heart of loss.
4676	What, Eros, Eros!
4677	
4678	[Enter CLEOPATRA]
4679	
4680	Ah, thou spell! Avaunt!
4681	
4682	CLEOPATRA	Why is my lord enraged against his love?
4683	
4684	MARK ANTONY	Vanish, or I shall give thee thy deserving,
4685	And blemish Caesar's triumph. Let him take thee,
4686	And hoist thee up to the shouting plebeians:
4687	Follow his chariot, like the greatest spot
4688	Of all thy sex; most monster-like, be shown
4689	For poor'st diminutives, for doits; and let
4690	Patient Octavia plough thy visage up
4691	With her prepared nails.
4692	
4693	[Exit CLEOPATRA]
4694	
4695	'Tis well thou'rt gone,
4696	If it be well to live; but better 'twere
4697	Thou fell'st into my fury, for one death
4698	Might have prevented many. Eros, ho!
4699	The shirt of Nessus is upon me: teach me,
4700	Alcides, thou mine ancestor, thy rage:
4701	Let me lodge Lichas on the horns o' the moon;
4702	And with those hands, that grasp'd the heaviest club,
4703	Subdue my worthiest self. The witch shall die:
4704	To the young Roman boy she hath sold me, and I fall
4705	Under this plot; she dies for't. Eros, ho!
4706	
4707	[Exit]
4708	
4709	
4710	
4711	
4712	ANTONY AND CLEOPATRA
4713	
4714	
4715	ACT IV
4716	
4717	
4718	SCENE XIII	Alexandria. Cleopatra's palace.
4719	
4720	
4721	[Enter CLEOPATRA, CHARMIAN, IRAS, and MARDIAN]
4722	
4723	CLEOPATRA	Help me, my women! O, he is more mad
4724	Than Telamon for his shield; the boar of Thessaly
4725	Was never so emboss'd.
4726	
4727	CHARMIAN	To the monument!
4728	There lock yourself, and send him word you are dead.
4729	The soul and body rive not more in parting
4730	Than greatness going off.
4731	
4732	CLEOPATRA	To the monument!
4733	Mardian, go tell him I have slain myself;
4734	Say, that the last I spoke was 'Antony,'
4735	And word it, prithee, piteously: hence, Mardian,
4736	And bring me how he takes my death.
4737	To the monument!
4738	
4739	[Exeunt]
4740	
4741	
4742	
4743	
4744	ANTONY AND CLEOPATRA
4745	
4746	
4747	ACT IV
4748	
4749	
4750	
4751	SCENE XIV	The same. Another room.
4752	
4753	
4754	[Enter MARK ANTONY and EROS]
4755	
4756	MARK ANTONY	Eros, thou yet behold'st me?
4757	
4758	EROS	Ay, noble lord.
4759	
4760	MARK ANTONY	Sometimes we see a cloud that's dragonish;
4761	A vapour sometime like a bear or lion,
4762	A tower'd citadel, a pendent rock,
4763	A forked mountain, or blue promontory
4764	With trees upon't, that nod unto the world,
4765	And mock our eyes with air: thou hast seen
4766	these signs;
4767	They are black vesper's pageants.
4768	
4769	EROS	Ay, my lord,
4770	
4771	MARK ANTONY	That which is now a horse, even with a thought
4772	The rack dislimns, and makes it indistinct,
4773	As water is in water.
4774	
4775	EROS	It does, my lord.
4776	
4777	MARK ANTONY	My good knave Eros, now thy captain is
4778	Even such a body: here I am Antony:
4779	Yet cannot hold this visible shape, my knave.
4780	I made these wars for Egypt: and the queen,--
4781	Whose heart I thought I had, for she had mine;
4782	Which whilst it was mine had annex'd unto't
4783	A million more, now lost,--she, Eros, has
4784	Pack'd cards with Caesar, and false-play'd my glory
4785	Unto an enemy's triumph.
4786	Nay, weep not, gentle Eros; there is left us
4787	Ourselves to end ourselves.
4788	
4789	[Enter MARDIAN]
4790	
4791	O! thy vile lady!
4792	She has robb'd me of my sword.
4793	
4794	MARDIAN	No, Antony;
4795	My mistress loved thee, and her fortunes mingled
4796	With thine entirely.
4797	
4798	MARK ANTONY	Hence, saucy eunuch; peace!
4799	She hath betray'd me and shall die the death.
4800	
4801	MARDIAN	Death of one person can be paid but once,
4802	And that she has discharged: what thou wouldst do
4803	Is done unto thy hand: the last she spake
4804	Was 'Antony! most noble Antony!'
4805	Then in the midst a tearing groan did break
4806	The name of Antony; it was divided
4807	Between her heart and lips: she render'd life,
4808	Thy name so buried in her.
4809	
4810	MARK ANTONY	Dead, then?
4811	
4812	MARDIAN	Dead.
4813	
4814	MARK ANTONY	Unarm, Eros; the long day's task is done,
4815	And we must sleep.
4816	
4817	[To MARDIAN]
4818	
4819	That thou depart'st hence safe,
4820	Does pay thy labour richly; go.
4821	
4822	[Exit MARDIAN]
4823	
4824	Off, pluck off:
4825	The seven-fold shield of Ajax cannot keep
4826	The battery from my heart. O, cleave, my sides!
4827	Heart, once be stronger than thy continent,
4828	Crack thy frail case! Apace, Eros, apace.
4829	No more a soldier: bruised pieces, go;
4830	You have been nobly borne. From me awhile.
4831	
4832	[Exit EROS]
4833	
4834	I will o'ertake thee, Cleopatra, and
4835	Weep for my pardon. So it must be, for now
4836	All length is torture: since the torch is out,
4837	Lie down, and stray no farther: now all labour
4838	Mars what it does; yea, very force entangles
4839	Itself with strength: seal then, and all is done.
4840	Eros!--I come, my queen:--Eros!--Stay for me:
4841	Where souls do couch on flowers, we'll hand in hand,
4842	And with our sprightly port make the ghosts gaze:
4843	Dido and her AEneas shall want troops,
4844	And all the haunt be ours. Come, Eros, Eros!
4845	
4846	[Re-enter EROS]
4847	
4848	EROS	What would my lord?
4849	
4850	MARK ANTONY	Since Cleopatra died,
4851	I have lived in such dishonour, that the gods
4852	Detest my baseness. I, that with my sword
4853	Quarter'd the world, and o'er green Neptune's back
4854	With ships made cities, condemn myself to lack
4855	The courage of a woman; less noble mind
4856	Than she which by her death our Caesar tells
4857	'I am conqueror of myself.' Thou art sworn, Eros,
4858	That, when the exigent should come, which now
4859	Is come indeed, when I should see behind me
4860	The inevitable prosecution of
4861	Disgrace and horror, that, on my command,
4862	Thou then wouldst kill me: do't; the time is come:
4863	Thou strikest not me, 'tis Caesar thou defeat'st.
4864	Put colour in thy cheek.
4865	
4866	EROS	The gods withhold me!
4867	Shall I do that which all the Parthian darts,
4868	Though enemy, lost aim, and could not?
4869	
4870	MARK ANTONY	Eros,
4871	Wouldst thou be window'd in great Rome and see
4872	Thy master thus with pleach'd arms, bending down
4873	His corrigible neck, his face subdued
4874	To penetrative shame, whilst the wheel'd seat
4875	Of fortunate Caesar, drawn before him, branded
4876	His baseness that ensued?
4877	
4878	EROS	I would not see't.
4879	
4880	MARK ANTONY	Come, then; for with a wound I must be cured.
4881	Draw that thy honest sword, which thou hast worn
4882	Most useful for thy country.
4883	
4884	EROS	O, sir, pardon me!
4885	
4886	MARK ANTONY	When I did make thee free, sworest thou not then
4887	To do this when I bade thee? Do it at once;
4888	Or thy precedent services are all
4889	But accidents unpurposed. Draw, and come.
4890	
4891	EROS	Turn from me, then, that noble countenance,
4892	Wherein the worship of the whole world lies.
4893	
4894	MARK ANTONY	Lo thee!
4895	
4896	[Turning from him]
4897	
4898	EROS	My sword is drawn.
4899	
4900	MARK ANTONY	                  Then let it do at once
4901	The thing why thou hast drawn it.
4902	
4903	EROS	My dear master,
4904	My captain, and my emperor, let me say,
4905	Before I strike this bloody stroke, farewell.
4906	
4907	MARK ANTONY	'Tis said, man; and farewell.
4908	
4909	EROS	Farewell, great chief. Shall I strike now?
4910	
4911	MARK ANTONY	Now, Eros.
4912	
4913	EROS	Why, there then: thus I do escape the sorrow
4914	Of Antony's death.
4915	
4916	[Kills himself]
4917	
4918	MARK ANTONY	                  Thrice-nobler than myself!
4919	Thou teachest me, O valiant Eros, what
4920	I should, and thou couldst not. My queen and Eros
4921	Have by their brave instruction got upon me
4922	A nobleness in record: but I will be
4923	A bridegroom in my death, and run into't
4924	As to a lover's bed. Come, then; and, Eros,
4925	Thy master dies thy scholar: to do thus
4926	
4927	[Falling on his sword]
4928	
4929	I learn'd of thee. How! not dead? not dead?
4930	The guard, ho! O, dispatch me!
4931	
4932	[Enter DERCETAS and Guard]
4933	
4934	First Guard	What's the noise?
4935	
4936	MARK ANTONY	I have done my work in, friends: O, make an end
4937	Of what I have begun.
4938	
4939	Second Guard	The star is fall'n.
4940	
4941	First Guard	And time is at his period.
4942	
4943	All	Alas, and woe!
4944	
4945	MARK ANTONY	Let him that loves me strike me dead.
4946	
4947	First Guard	Not I.
4948	
4949	Second Guard	Nor I.
4950	
4951	Third Guard	Nor any one.
4952	
4953	[Exeunt Guard]
4954	
4955	DERCETAS	Thy death and fortunes bid thy followers fly.
4956	This sword but shown to Caesar, with this tidings,
4957	Shall enter me with him.
4958	
4959	[Enter DIOMEDES]
4960	
4961	DIOMEDES	Where's Antony?
4962	
4963	DERCETAS	                  There, Diomed there.
4964	
4965	DIOMEDES	Lives he?
4966	Wilt thou not answer, man?
4967	
4968	[Exit DERCETAS]
4969	
4970	MARK ANTONY	Art thou there, Diomed? Draw thy sword, and give me
4971	Sufficing strokes for death.
4972	
4973	DIOMEDES	Most absolute lord,
4974	My mistress Cleopatra sent me to thee.
4975	
4976	MARK ANTONY	When did she send thee?
4977	
4978	DIOMEDES	Now, my lord.
4979	
4980	MARK ANTONY	Where is she?
4981	
4982	DIOMEDES	Lock'd in her monument. She had a prophesying fear
4983	Of what hath come to pass: for when she saw--
4984	Which never shall be found--you did suspect
4985	She had disposed with Caesar, and that your rage
4986	Would not be purged, she sent you word she was dead;
4987	But, fearing since how it might work, hath sent
4988	Me to proclaim the truth; and I am come,
4989	I dread, too late.
4990	
4991	MARK ANTONY	Too late, good Diomed: call my guard, I prithee.
4992	
4993	DIOMEDES	What, ho, the emperor's guard! The guard, what, ho!
4994	Come, your lord calls!
4995	
4996	[Enter four or five of the Guard of MARK ANTONY]
4997	
4998	MARK ANTONY	Bear me, good friends, where Cleopatra bides;
4999	'Tis the last service that I shall command you.
5000	
5001	First Guard	Woe, woe are we, sir, you may not live to wear
5002	All your true followers out.
5003	
5004	All	Most heavy day!
5005	
5006	MARK ANTONY	Nay, good my fellows, do not please sharp fate
5007	To grace it with your sorrows: bid that welcome
5008	Which comes to punish us, and we punish it
5009	Seeming to bear it lightly. Take me up:
5010	I have led you oft: carry me now, good friends,
5011	And have my thanks for all.
5012	
5013	[Exeunt, bearing MARK ANTONY]
5014	
5015	
5016	
5017	
5018	ANTONY AND CLEOPATRA
5019	
5020	
5021	ACT IV
5022	
5023	
5024	
5025	SCENE XV	The same. A monument.
5026	
5027	
5028	[Enter CLEOPATRA and her maids aloft, with
5029	CHARMIAN and IRAS]
5030	
5031	CLEOPATRA	O Charmian, I will never go from hence.
5032	
5033	CHARMIAN	Be comforted, dear madam.
5034	
5035	CLEOPATRA	No, I will not:
5036	All strange and terrible events are welcome,
5037	But comforts we despise; our size of sorrow,
5038	Proportion'd to our cause, must be as great
5039	As that which makes it.
5040	
5041	[Enter, below, DIOMEDES]
5042	
5043	How now! is he dead?
5044	
5045	DIOMEDES	His death's upon him, but not dead.
5046	Look out o' the other side your monument;
5047	His guard have brought him thither.
5048	
5049	[Enter, below, MARK ANTONY, borne by the Guard]
5050	
5051	CLEOPATRA	O sun,
5052	Burn the great sphere thou movest in!
5053	darkling stand
5054	The varying shore o' the world. O Antony,
5055	Antony, Antony! Help, Charmian, help, Iras, help;
5056	Help, friends below; let's draw him hither.
5057	
5058	MARK ANTONY	Peace!
5059	Not Caesar's valour hath o'erthrown Antony,
5060	But Antony's hath triumph'd on itself.
5061	
5062	CLEOPATRA	So it should be, that none but Antony
5063	Should conquer Antony; but woe 'tis so!
5064	
5065	MARK ANTONY	I am dying, Egypt, dying; only
5066	I here importune death awhile, until
5067	Of many thousand kisses the poor last
5068	I lay up thy lips.
5069	
5070	CLEOPATRA	                  I dare not, dear,--
5071	Dear my lord, pardon,--I dare not,
5072	Lest I be taken: not the imperious show
5073	Of the full-fortuned Caesar ever shall
5074	Be brooch'd with me; if knife, drugs,
5075	serpents, have
5076	Edge, sting, or operation, I am safe:
5077	Your wife Octavia, with her modest eyes
5078	And still conclusion, shall acquire no honour
5079	Demuring upon me. But come, come, Antony,--
5080	Help me, my women,--we must draw thee up:
5081	Assist, good friends.
5082	
5083	MARK ANTONY	O, quick, or I am gone.
5084	
5085	CLEOPATRA	Here's sport indeed! How heavy weighs my lord!
5086	Our strength is all gone into heaviness,
5087	That makes the weight: had I great Juno's power,
5088	The strong-wing'd Mercury should fetch thee up,
5089	And set thee by Jove's side. Yet come a little,--
5090	Wishes were ever fools,--O, come, come, come;
5091	
5092	[They heave MARK ANTONY aloft to CLEOPATRA]
5093	
5094	And welcome, welcome! die where thou hast lived:
5095	Quicken with kissing: had my lips that power,
5096	Thus would I wear them out.
5097	
5098	All	A heavy sight!
5099	
5100	MARK ANTONY	I am dying, Egypt, dying:
5101	Give me some wine, and let me speak a little.
5102	
5103	CLEOPATRA	No, let me speak; and let me rail so high,
5104	That the false housewife Fortune break her wheel,
5105	Provoked by my offence.
5106	
5107	MARK ANTONY	One word, sweet queen:
5108	Of Caesar seek your honour, with your safety. O!
5109	
5110	CLEOPATRA	They do not go together.
5111	
5112	MARK ANTONY	Gentle, hear me:
5113	None about Caesar trust but Proculeius.
5114	
5115	CLEOPATRA	My resolution and my hands I'll trust;
5116	None about Caesar.
5117	
5118	MARK ANTONY	The miserable change now at my end
5119	Lament nor sorrow at; but please your thoughts
5120	In feeding them with those my former fortunes
5121	Wherein I lived, the greatest prince o' the world,
5122	The noblest; and do now not basely die,
5123	Not cowardly put off my helmet to
5124	My countryman,--a Roman by a Roman
5125	Valiantly vanquish'd. Now my spirit is going;
5126	I can no more.
5127	
5128	CLEOPATRA	                  Noblest of men, woo't die?
5129	Hast thou no care of me? shall I abide
5130	In this dull world, which in thy absence is
5131	No better than a sty? O, see, my women,
5132	
5133	[MARK ANTONY dies]
5134	
5135	The crown o' the earth doth melt. My lord!
5136	O, wither'd is the garland of the war,
5137	The soldier's pole is fall'n: young boys and girls
5138	Are level now with men; the odds is gone,
5139	And there is nothing left remarkable
5140	Beneath the visiting moon.
5141	
5142	[Faints]
5143	
5144	CHARMIAN	O, quietness, lady!
5145	
5146	IRAS	She is dead too, our sovereign.
5147	
5148	CHARMIAN	Lady!
5149	
5150	IRAS	Madam!
5151	
5152	CHARMIAN	O madam, madam, madam!
5153	
5154	IRAS	Royal Egypt, Empress!
5155	
5156	CHARMIAN	Peace, peace, Iras!
5157	
5158	CLEOPATRA	No more, but e'en a woman, and commanded
5159	By such poor passion as the maid that milks
5160	And does the meanest chares. It were for me
5161	To throw my sceptre at the injurious gods;
5162	To tell them that this world did equal theirs
5163	Till they had stol'n our jewel. All's but naught;
5164	Patience is scottish, and impatience does
5165	Become a dog that's mad: then is it sin
5166	To rush into the secret house of death,
5167	Ere death dare come to us? How do you, women?
5168	What, what! good cheer! Why, how now, Charmian!
5169	My noble girls! Ah, women, women, look,
5170	Our lamp is spent, it's out! Good sirs, take heart:
5171	We'll bury him; and then, what's brave,
5172	what's noble,
5173	Let's do it after the high Roman fashion,
5174	And make death proud to take us. Come, away:
5175	This case of that huge spirit now is cold:
5176	Ah, women, women! come; we have no friend
5177	But resolution, and the briefest end.
5178	
5179	[Exeunt; those above bearing off MARK ANTONY's body]
5180	
5181	
5182	
5183	
5184	ANTONY AND CLEOPATRA
5185	
5186	
5187	ACT V
5188	
5189	
5190	
5191	SCENE I	Alexandria. OCTAVIUS CAESAR's camp.
5192	
5193	
5194	[Enter OCTAVIUS CAESAR, AGRIPPA, DOLABELLA, MECAENAS,
5195	GALLUS, PROCULEIUS, and others, his council of war]
5196	
5197	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Go to him, Dolabella, bid him yield;
5198	Being so frustrate, tell him he mocks
5199	The pauses that he makes.
5200	
5201	DOLABELLA	Caesar, I shall.
5202	
5203	[Exit]
5204	
5205	[Enter DERCETAS, with the sword of MARK ANTONY]
5206	
5207	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Wherefore is that? and what art thou that darest
5208	Appear thus to us?
5209	
5210	DERCETAS	                  I am call'd Dercetas;
5211	Mark Antony I served, who best was worthy
5212	Best to be served: whilst he stood up and spoke,
5213	He was my master; and I wore my life
5214	To spend upon his haters. If thou please
5215	To take me to thee, as I was to him
5216	I'll be to Caesar; if thou pleasest not,
5217	I yield thee up my life.
5218	
5219	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	What is't thou say'st?
5220	
5221	DERCETAS	I say, O Caesar, Antony is dead.
5222	
5223	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	The breaking of so great a thing should make
5224	A greater crack: the round world
5225	Should have shook lions into civil streets,
5226	And citizens to their dens: the death of Antony
5227	Is not a single doom; in the name lay
5228	A moiety of the world.
5229	
5230	DERCETAS	He is dead, Caesar:
5231	Not by a public minister of justice,
5232	Nor by a hired knife; but that self hand,
5233	Which writ his honour in the acts it did,
5234	Hath, with the courage which the heart did lend it,
5235	Splitted the heart. This is his sword;
5236	I robb'd his wound of it; behold it stain'd
5237	With his most noble blood.
5238	
5239	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Look you sad, friends?
5240	The gods rebuke me, but it is tidings
5241	To wash the eyes of kings.
5242	
5243	AGRIPPA	And strange it is,
5244	That nature must compel us to lament
5245	Our most persisted deeds.
5246	
5247	MECAENAS	His taints and honours
5248	Waged equal with him.
5249	
5250	AGRIPPA	A rarer spirit never
5251	Did steer humanity: but you, gods, will give us
5252	Some faults to make us men. Caesar is touch'd.
5253	
5254	MECAENAS	When such a spacious mirror's set before him,
5255	He needs must see himself.
5256	
5257	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	O Antony!
5258	I have follow'd thee to this; but we do lance
5259	Diseases in our bodies: I must perforce
5260	Have shown to thee such a declining day,
5261	Or look on thine; we could not stall together
5262	In the whole world: but yet let me lament,
5263	With tears as sovereign as the blood of hearts,
5264	That thou, my brother, my competitor
5265	In top of all design, my mate in empire,
5266	Friend and companion in the front of war,
5267	The arm of mine own body, and the heart
5268	Where mine his thoughts did kindle,--that our stars,
5269	Unreconciliable, should divide
5270	Our equalness to this. Hear me, good friends--
5271	But I will tell you at some meeter season:
5272	
5273	[Enter an Egyptian]
5274	
5275	The business of this man looks out of him;
5276	We'll hear him what he says. Whence are you?
5277	
5278	Egyptian	A poor Egyptian yet. The queen my mistress,
5279	Confined in all she has, her monument,
5280	Of thy intents desires instruction,
5281	That she preparedly may frame herself
5282	To the way she's forced to.
5283	
5284	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Bid her have good heart:
5285	She soon shall know of us, by some of ours,
5286	How honourable and how kindly we
5287	Determine for her; for Caesar cannot live
5288	To be ungentle.
5289	
5290	Egyptian	So the gods preserve thee!
5291	
5292	[Exit]
5293	
5294	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Come hither, Proculeius. Go and say,
5295	We purpose her no shame: give her what comforts
5296	The quality of her passion shall require,
5297	Lest, in her greatness, by some mortal stroke
5298	She do defeat us; for her life in Rome
5299	Would be eternal in our triumph: go,
5300	And with your speediest bring us what she says,
5301	And how you find of her.
5302	
5303	PROCULEIUS	Caesar, I shall.
5304	
5305	[Exit]
5306	
5307	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Gallus, go you along.
5308	
5309	[Exit GALLUS]
5310	
5311	Where's Dolabella,
5312	To second Proculeius?
5313	
5314	All	Dolabella!
5315	
5316	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Let him alone, for I remember now
5317	How he's employ'd: he shall in time be ready.
5318	Go with me to my tent; where you shall see
5319	How hardly I was drawn into this war;
5320	How calm and gentle I proceeded still
5321	In all my writings: go with me, and see
5322	What I can show in this.
5323	
5324	[Exeunt]
5325	
5326	
5327	
5328	
5329	ANTONY AND CLEOPATRA
5330	
5331	
5332	ACT V
5333	
5334	
5335	
5336	SCENE II	Alexandria. A room in the monument.
5337	
5338	
5339	[Enter CLEOPATRA, CHARMIAN, and IRAS]
5340	
5341	CLEOPATRA	My desolation does begin to make
5342	A better life. 'Tis paltry to be Caesar;
5343	Not being Fortune, he's but Fortune's knave,
5344	A minister of her will: and it is great
5345	To do that thing that ends all other deeds;
5346	Which shackles accidents and bolts up change;
5347	Which sleeps, and never palates more the dug,
5348	The beggar's nurse and Caesar's.
5349	
5350	[Enter, to the gates of the monument, PROCULEIUS,
5351	GALLUS and Soldiers]
5352	
5353	PROCULEIUS	Caesar sends greeting to the Queen of Egypt;
5354	And bids thee study on what fair demands
5355	Thou mean'st to have him grant thee.
5356	
5357	CLEOPATRA	What's thy name?
5358	
5359	PROCULEIUS	My name is Proculeius.
5360	
5361	CLEOPATRA	Antony
5362	Did tell me of you, bade me trust you; but
5363	I do not greatly care to be deceived,
5364	That have no use for trusting. If your master
5365	Would have a queen his beggar, you must tell him,
5366	That majesty, to keep decorum, must
5367	No less beg than a kingdom: if he please
5368	To give me conquer'd Egypt for my son,
5369	He gives me so much of mine own, as I
5370	Will kneel to him with thanks.
5371	
5372	PROCULEIUS	Be of good cheer;
5373	You're fall'n into a princely hand, fear nothing:
5374	Make your full reference freely to my lord,
5375	Who is so full of grace, that it flows over
5376	On all that need: let me report to him
5377	Your sweet dependency; and you shall find
5378	A conqueror that will pray in aid for kindness,
5379	Where he for grace is kneel'd to.
5380	
5381	CLEOPATRA	Pray you, tell him
5382	I am his fortune's vassal, and I send him
5383	The greatness he has got. I hourly learn
5384	A doctrine of obedience; and would gladly
5385	Look him i' the face.
5386	
5387	PROCULEIUS	This I'll report, dear lady.
5388	Have comfort, for I know your plight is pitied
5389	Of him that caused it.
5390	
5391	GALLUS	You see how easily she may be surprised:
5392	
5393	[Here PROCULEIUS and two of the Guard ascend the
5394	monument by a ladder placed against a window, and,
5395	having descended, come behind CLEOPATRA. Some of
5396	the Guard unbar and open the gates]
5397	
5398	[To PROCULEIUS and the Guard]
5399	
5400	Guard her till Caesar come.
5401	
5402	[Exit]
5403	
5404	IRAS	Royal queen!
5405	
5406	CHARMIAN	O Cleopatra! thou art taken, queen:
5407	
5408	CLEOPATRA	Quick, quick, good hands.
5409	
5410	[Drawing a dagger]
5411	
5412	PROCULEIUS	Hold, worthy lady, hold:
5413	
5414	[Seizes and disarms her]
5415	
5416	Do not yourself such wrong, who are in this
5417	Relieved, but not betray'd.
5418	
5419	CLEOPATRA	What, of death too,
5420	That rids our dogs of languish?
5421	
5422	PROCULEIUS	Cleopatra,
5423	Do not abuse my master's bounty by
5424	The undoing of yourself: let the world see
5425	His nobleness well acted, which your death
5426	Will never let come forth.
5427	
5428	CLEOPATRA	Where art thou, death?
5429	Come hither, come! come, come, and take a queen
5430	Worthy many babes and beggars!
5431	
5432	PROCULEIUS	O, temperance, lady!
5433	
5434	CLEOPATRA	Sir, I will eat no meat, I'll not drink, sir;
5435	If idle talk will once be necessary,
5436	I'll not sleep neither: this mortal house I'll ruin,
5437	Do Caesar what he can. Know, sir, that I
5438	Will not wait pinion'd at your master's court;
5439	Nor once be chastised with the sober eye
5440	Of dull Octavia. Shall they hoist me up
5441	And show me to the shouting varletry
5442	Of censuring Rome? Rather a ditch in Egypt
5443	Be gentle grave unto me! rather on Nilus' mud
5444	Lay me stark naked, and let the water-flies
5445	Blow me into abhorring! rather make
5446	My country's high pyramides my gibbet,
5447	And hang me up in chains!
5448	
5449	PROCULEIUS	You do extend
5450	These thoughts of horror further than you shall
5451	Find cause in Caesar.
5452	
5453	[Enter DOLABELLA]
5454	
5455	DOLABELLA	Proculeius,
5456	What thou hast done thy master Caesar knows,
5457	And he hath sent for thee: for the queen,
5458	I'll take her to my guard.
5459	
5460	PROCULEIUS	So, Dolabella,
5461	It shall content me best: be gentle to her.
5462	
5463	[To CLEOPATRA]
5464	
5465	To Caesar I will speak what you shall please,
5466	If you'll employ me to him.
5467	
5468	CLEOPATRA	Say, I would die.
5469	
5470	[Exeunt PROCULEIUS and Soldiers]
5471	
5472	DOLABELLA	Most noble empress, you have heard of me?
5473	
5474	CLEOPATRA	I cannot tell.
5475	
5476	DOLABELLA	                  Assuredly you know me.
5477	
5478	CLEOPATRA	No matter, sir, what I have heard or known.
5479	You laugh when boys or women tell their dreams;
5480	Is't not your trick?
5481	
5482	DOLABELLA	I understand not, madam.
5483	
5484	CLEOPATRA	I dream'd there was an Emperor Antony:
5485	O, such another sleep, that I might see
5486	But such another man!
5487	
5488	DOLABELLA	If it might please ye,--
5489	
5490	CLEOPATRA	His face was as the heavens; and therein stuck
5491	A sun and moon, which kept their course,
5492	and lighted
5493	The little O, the earth.
5494	
5495	DOLABELLA	Most sovereign creature,--
5496	
5497	CLEOPATRA	His legs bestrid the ocean: his rear'd arm
5498	Crested the world: his voice was propertied
5499	As all the tuned spheres, and that to friends;
5500	But when he meant to quail and shake the orb,
5501	He was as rattling thunder. For his bounty,
5502	There was no winter in't; an autumn 'twas
5503	That grew the more by reaping: his delights
5504	Were dolphin-like; they show'd his back above
5505	The element they lived in: in his livery
5506	Walk'd crowns and crownets; realms and islands were
5507	As plates dropp'd from his pocket.
5508	
5509	DOLABELLA	Cleopatra!
5510	
5511	CLEOPATRA	Think you there was, or might be, such a man
5512	As this I dream'd of?
5513	
5514	DOLABELLA	Gentle madam, no.
5515	
5516	CLEOPATRA	You lie, up to the hearing of the gods.
5517	But, if there be, or ever were, one such,
5518	It's past the size of dreaming: nature wants stuff
5519	To vie strange forms with fancy; yet, to imagine
5520	And Antony, were nature's piece 'gainst fancy,
5521	Condemning shadows quite.
5522	
5523	DOLABELLA	Hear me, good madam.
5524	Your loss is as yourself, great; and you bear it
5525	As answering to the weight: would I might never
5526	O'ertake pursued success, but I do feel,
5527	By the rebound of yours, a grief that smites
5528	My very heart at root.
5529	
5530	CLEOPATRA	I thank you, sir,
5531	Know you what Caesar means to do with me?
5532	
5533	DOLABELLA	I am loath to tell you what I would you knew.
5534	
5535	CLEOPATRA	Nay, pray you, sir,--
5536	
5537	DOLABELLA	Though he be honourable,--
5538	
5539	CLEOPATRA	He'll lead me, then, in triumph?
5540	
5541	DOLABELLA	Madam, he will; I know't.
5542	
5543	[Flourish, and shout within, 'Make way there:
5544	Octavius Caesar!']
5545	
5546	[Enter OCTAVIUS CAESAR, GALLUS, PROCULEIUS,
5547	MECAENAS, SELEUCUS, and others of his Train]
5548	
5549	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Which is the Queen of Egypt?
5550	
5551	DOLABELLA	It is the emperor, madam.
5552	
5553	[CLEOPATRA kneels]
5554	
5555	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Arise, you shall not kneel:
5556	I pray you, rise; rise, Egypt.
5557	
5558	CLEOPATRA	Sir, the gods
5559	Will have it thus; my master and my lord
5560	I must obey.
5561	
5562	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	                  Take to you no hard thoughts:
5563	The record of what injuries you did us,
5564	Though written in our flesh, we shall remember
5565	As things but done by chance.
5566	
5567	CLEOPATRA	Sole sir o' the world,
5568	I cannot project mine own cause so well
5569	To make it clear; but do confess I have
5570	Been laden with like frailties which before
5571	Have often shamed our sex.
5572	
5573	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Cleopatra, know,
5574	We will extenuate rather than enforce:
5575	If you apply yourself to our intents,
5576	Which towards you are most gentle, you shall find
5577	A benefit in this change; but if you seek
5578	To lay on me a cruelty, by taking
5579	Antony's course, you shall bereave yourself
5580	Of my good purposes, and put your children
5581	To that destruction which I'll guard them from,
5582	If thereon you rely. I'll take my leave.
5583	
5584	CLEOPATRA	And may, through all the world: 'tis yours; and we,
5585	Your scutcheons and your signs of conquest, shall
5586	Hang in what place you please. Here, my good lord.
5587	
5588	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	You shall advise me in all for Cleopatra.
5589	
5590	CLEOPATRA	This is the brief of money, plate, and jewels,
5591	I am possess'd of: 'tis exactly valued;
5592	Not petty things admitted. Where's Seleucus?
5593	
5594	SELEUCUS	Here, madam.
5595	
5596	CLEOPATRA	This is my treasurer: let him speak, my lord,
5597	Upon his peril, that I have reserved
5598	To myself nothing. Speak the truth, Seleucus.
5599	
5600	SELEUCUS	Madam,
5601	I had rather seal my lips, than, to my peril,
5602	Speak that which is not.
5603	
5604	CLEOPATRA	What have I kept back?
5605	
5606	SELEUCUS	Enough to purchase what you have made known.
5607	
5608	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Nay, blush not, Cleopatra; I approve
5609	Your wisdom in the deed.
5610	
5611	CLEOPATRA	See, Caesar! O, behold,
5612	How pomp is follow'd! mine will now be yours;
5613	And, should we shift estates, yours would be mine.
5614	The ingratitude of this Seleucus does
5615	Even make me wild: O slave, of no more trust
5616	Than love that's hired! What, goest thou back? thou shalt
5617	Go back, I warrant thee; but I'll catch thine eyes,
5618	Though they had wings: slave, soulless villain, dog!
5619	O rarely base!
5620	
5621	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	                  Good queen, let us entreat you.
5622	
5623	CLEOPATRA	O Caesar, what a wounding shame is this,
5624	That thou, vouchsafing here to visit me,
5625	Doing the honour of thy lordliness
5626	To one so meek, that mine own servant should
5627	Parcel the sum of my disgraces by
5628	Addition of his envy! Say, good Caesar,
5629	That I some lady trifles have reserved,
5630	Immoment toys, things of such dignity
5631	As we greet modern friends withal; and say,
5632	Some nobler token I have kept apart
5633	For Livia and Octavia, to induce
5634	Their mediation; must I be unfolded
5635	With one that I have bred? The gods! it smites me
5636	Beneath the fall I have.
5637	
5638	[To SELEUCUS]
5639	
5640	Prithee, go hence;
5641	Or I shall show the cinders of my spirits
5642	Through the ashes of my chance: wert thou a man,
5643	Thou wouldst have mercy on me.
5644	
5645	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Forbear, Seleucus.
5646	
5647	[Exit SELEUCUS]
5648	
5649	CLEOPATRA	Be it known, that we, the greatest, are misthought
5650	For things that others do; and, when we fall,
5651	We answer others' merits in our name,
5652	Are therefore to be pitied.
5653	
5654	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Cleopatra,
5655	Not what you have reserved, nor what acknowledged,
5656	Put we i' the roll of conquest: still be't yours,
5657	Bestow it at your pleasure; and believe,
5658	Caesar's no merchant, to make prize with you
5659	Of things that merchants sold. Therefore be cheer'd;
5660	Make not your thoughts your prisons: no, dear queen;
5661	For we intend so to dispose you as
5662	Yourself shall give us counsel. Feed, and sleep:
5663	Our care and pity is so much upon you,
5664	That we remain your friend; and so, adieu.
5665	
5666	CLEOPATRA	My master, and my lord!
5667	
5668	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Not so. Adieu.
5669	
5670	[Flourish. Exeunt OCTAVIUS CAESAR and his train]
5671	
5672	CLEOPATRA	He words me, girls, he words me, that I should not
5673	Be noble to myself: but, hark thee, Charmian.
5674	
5675	[Whispers CHARMIAN]
5676	
5677	IRAS	Finish, good lady; the bright day is done,
5678	And we are for the dark.
5679	
5680	CLEOPATRA	Hie thee again:
5681	I have spoke already, and it is provided;
5682	Go put it to the haste.
5683	
5684	CHARMIAN	Madam, I will.
5685	
5686	[Re-enter DOLABELLA]
5687	
5688	DOLABELLA	Where is the queen?
5689	
5690	CHARMIAN	Behold, sir.
5691	
5692	[Exit]
5693	
5694	CLEOPATRA	Dolabella!
5695	
5696	DOLABELLA	Madam, as thereto sworn by your command,
5697	Which my love makes religion to obey,
5698	I tell you this: Caesar through Syria
5699	Intends his journey; and within three days
5700	You with your children will he send before:
5701	Make your best use of this: I have perform'd
5702	Your pleasure and my promise.
5703	
5704	CLEOPATRA	Dolabella,
5705	I shall remain your debtor.
5706	
5707	DOLABELLA	I your servant,
5708	Adieu, good queen; I must attend on Caesar.
5709	
5710	CLEOPATRA	Farewell, and thanks.
5711	
5712	[Exit DOLABELLA]
5713	
5714	Now, Iras, what think'st thou?
5715	Thou, an Egyptian puppet, shalt be shown
5716	In Rome, as well as I	mechanic slaves
5717	With greasy aprons, rules, and hammers, shall
5718	Uplift us to the view; in their thick breaths,
5719	Rank of gross diet, shall be enclouded,
5720	And forced to drink their vapour.
5721	
5722	IRAS	The gods forbid!
5723	
5724	CLEOPATRA	Nay, 'tis most certain, Iras: saucy lictors
5725	Will catch at us, like strumpets; and scald rhymers
5726	Ballad us out o' tune: the quick comedians
5727	Extemporally will stage us, and present
5728	Our Alexandrian revels; Antony
5729	Shall be brought drunken forth, and I shall see
5730	Some squeaking Cleopatra boy my greatness
5731	I' the posture of a whore.
5732	
5733	IRAS	O the good gods!
5734	
5735	CLEOPATRA	Nay, that's certain.
5736	
5737	IRAS	I'll never see 't; for, I am sure, my nails
5738	Are stronger than mine eyes.
5739	
5740	CLEOPATRA	Why, that's the way
5741	To fool their preparation, and to conquer
5742	Their most absurd intents.
5743	
5744	[Re-enter CHARMIAN]
5745	
5746	Now, Charmian!
5747	Show me, my women, like a queen: go fetch
5748	My best attires: I am again for Cydnus,
5749	To meet Mark Antony: sirrah Iras, go.
5750	Now, noble Charmian, we'll dispatch indeed;
5751	And, when thou hast done this chare, I'll give thee leave
5752	To play till doomsday. Bring our crown and all.
5753	Wherefore's this noise?
5754	
5755	[Exit IRAS. A noise within]
5756	
5757	[Enter a Guardsman]
5758	
5759	Guard	Here is a rural fellow
5760	That will not be denied your highness presence:
5761	He brings you figs.
5762	
5763	CLEOPATRA	Let him come in.
5764	
5765	[Exit Guardsman]
5766	
5767	What poor an instrument
5768	May do a noble deed! he brings me liberty.
5769	My resolution's placed, and I have nothing
5770	Of woman in me: now from head to foot
5771	I am marble-constant; now the fleeting moon
5772	No planet is of mine.
5773	
5774	[Re-enter Guardsman, with Clown bringing in a basket]
5775	
5776	Guard	This is the man.
5777	
5778	CLEOPATRA	Avoid, and leave him.
5779	
5780	[Exit Guardsman]
5781	
5782	Hast thou the pretty worm of Nilus there,
5783	That kills and pains not?
5784	
5785	Clown	Truly, I have him: but I would not be the party
5786	that should desire you to touch him, for his biting
5787	is immortal; those that do die of it do seldom or
5788	never recover.
5789	
5790	CLEOPATRA	Rememberest thou any that have died on't?
5791	
5792	Clown	Very many, men and women too. I heard of one of
5793	them no longer than yesterday: a very honest woman,
5794	but something given to lie; as a woman should not
5795	do, but in the way of honesty: how she died of the
5796	biting of it, what pain she felt: truly, she makes
5797	a very good report o' the worm; but he that will
5798	believe all that they say, shall never be saved by
5799	half that they do: but this is most fallible, the
5800	worm's an odd worm.
5801	
5802	CLEOPATRA	Get thee hence; farewell.
5803	
5804	Clown	I wish you all joy of the worm.
5805	
5806	[Setting down his basket]
5807	
5808	CLEOPATRA	Farewell.
5809	
5810	Clown	You must think this, look you, that the worm will
5811	do his kind.
5812	
5813	CLEOPATRA	Ay, ay; farewell.
5814	
5815	Clown	Look you, the worm is not to be trusted but in the
5816	keeping of wise people; for, indeed, there is no
5817	goodness in worm.
5818	
5819	
5820	CLEOPATRA	Take thou no care; it shall be heeded.
5821	
5822	Clown	Very good. Give it nothing, I pray you, for it is
5823	not worth the feeding.
5824	
5825	CLEOPATRA	Will it eat me?
5826	
5827	Clown	You must not think I am so simple but I know the
5828	devil himself will not eat a woman: I know that a
5829	woman is a dish for the gods, if the devil dress her
5830	not. But, truly, these same whoreson devils do the
5831	gods great harm in their women; for in every ten
5832	that they make, the devils mar five.
5833	
5834	CLEOPATRA	Well, get thee gone; farewell.
5835	
5836	Clown	Yes, forsooth: I wish you joy o' the worm.
5837	
5838	[Exit]
5839	
5840	[Re-enter IRAS with a robe, crown, &c]
5841	
5842	CLEOPATRA	Give me my robe, put on my crown; I have
5843	Immortal longings in me: now no more
5844	The juice of Egypt's grape shall moist this lip:
5845	Yare, yare, good Iras; quick. Methinks I hear
5846	Antony call; I see him rouse himself
5847	To praise my noble act; I hear him mock
5848	The luck of Caesar, which the gods give men
5849	To excuse their after wrath: husband, I come:
5850	Now to that name my courage prove my title!
5851	I am fire and air; my other elements
5852	I give to baser life. So; have you done?
5853	Come then, and take the last warmth of my lips.
5854	Farewell, kind Charmian; Iras, long farewell.
5855	
5856	[Kisses them. IRAS falls and dies]
5857	
5858	Have I the aspic in my lips? Dost fall?
5859	If thou and nature can so gently part,
5860	The stroke of death is as a lover's pinch,
5861	Which hurts, and is desired. Dost thou lie still?
5862	If thus thou vanishest, thou tell'st the world
5863	It is not worth leave-taking.
5864	
5865	CHARMIAN	Dissolve, thick cloud, and rain; that I may say,
5866	The gods themselves do weep!
5867	
5868	CLEOPATRA	This proves me base:
5869	If she first meet the curled Antony,
5870	He'll make demand of her, and spend that kiss
5871	Which is my heaven to have. Come, thou
5872	mortal wretch,
5873	
5874	[To an asp, which she applies to her breast]
5875	
5876	With thy sharp teeth this knot intrinsicate
5877	Of life at once untie: poor venomous fool
5878	Be angry, and dispatch. O, couldst thou speak,
5879	That I might hear thee call great Caesar ass
5880	Unpolicied!
5881	
5882	CHARMIAN	          O eastern star!
5883	
5884	CLEOPATRA	Peace, peace!
5885	Dost thou not see my baby at my breast,
5886	That sucks the nurse asleep?
5887	
5888	CHARMIAN	O, break! O, break!
5889	
5890	CLEOPATRA	As sweet as balm, as soft as air, as gentle,--
5891	O Antony!--Nay, I will take thee too.
5892	
5893	[Applying another asp to her arm]
5894	
5895	What should I stay--
5896	
5897	[Dies]
5898	
5899	CHARMIAN	In this vile world? So, fare thee well.
5900	Now boast thee, death, in thy possession lies
5901	A lass unparallel'd. Downy windows, close;
5902	And golden Phoebus never be beheld
5903	Of eyes again so royal! Your crown's awry;
5904	I'll mend it, and then play.
5905	
5906	[Enter the Guard, rushing in]
5907	
5908	First Guard	Where is the queen?
5909	
5910	CHARMIAN	Speak softly, wake her not.
5911	
5912	First Guard	Caesar hath sent--
5913	
5914	CHARMIAN	                  Too slow a messenger.
5915	
5916	[Applies an asp]
5917	
5918	O, come apace, dispatch! I partly feel thee.
5919	
5920	First Guard	Approach, ho! All's not well: Caesar's beguiled.
5921	
5922	Second Guard	There's Dolabella sent from Caesar; call him.
5923	
5924	First Guard	What work is here! Charmian, is this well done?
5925	
5926	CHARMIAN	It is well done, and fitting for a princess
5927	Descended of so many royal kings.
5928	Ah, soldier!
5929	
5930	[Dies]
5931	
5932	[Re-enter DOLABELLA]
5933	
5934	DOLABELLA	How goes it here?
5935	
5936	Second Guard	                  All dead.
5937	
5938	DOLABELLA	Caesar, thy thoughts
5939	Touch their effects in this: thyself art coming
5940	To see perform'd the dreaded act which thou
5941	So sought'st to hinder.
5942	
5943	[Within  'A way there, a way for Caesar!']
5944	
5945	[Re-enter OCTAVIUS CAESAR and all his train marching]
5946	
5947	DOLABELLA	O sir, you are too sure an augurer;
5948	That you did fear is done.
5949	
5950	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Bravest at the last,
5951	She levell'd at our purposes, and, being royal,
5952	Took her own way. The manner of their deaths?
5953	I do not see them bleed.
5954	
5955	DOLABELLA	Who was last with them?
5956	
5957	First Guard	A simple countryman, that brought her figs:
5958	This was his basket.
5959	
5960	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Poison'd, then.
5961	
5962	First Guard	O Caesar,
5963	This Charmian lived but now; she stood and spake:
5964	I found her trimming up the diadem
5965	On her dead mistress; tremblingly she stood
5966	And on the sudden dropp'd.
5967	
5968	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	O noble weakness!
5969	If they had swallow'd poison, 'twould appear
5970	By external swelling: but she looks like sleep,
5971	As she would catch another Antony
5972	In her strong toil of grace.
5973	
5974	DOLABELLA	Here, on her breast,
5975	There is a vent of blood and something blown:
5976	The like is on her arm.
5977	
5978	First Guard	This is an aspic's trail: and these fig-leaves
5979	Have slime upon them, such as the aspic leaves
5980	Upon the caves of Nile.
5981	
5982	OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Most probable
5983	That so she died; for her physician tells me
5984	She hath pursued conclusions infinite
5985	Of easy ways to die. Take up her bed;
5986	And bear her women from the monument:
5987	She shall be buried by her Antony:
5988	No grave upon the earth shall clip in it
5989	A pair so famous. High events as these
5990	Strike those that make them; and their story is
5991	No less in pity than his glory which
5992	Brought them to be lamented. Our army shall
5993	In solemn show attend this funeral;
5994	And then to Rome. Come, Dolabella, see
5995	High order in this great solemnity.
5996	
5997	[Exeunt]
